</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="71495" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71495">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71495">R, ed, tp, h</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="71495">
This species was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Verhoeff, K. W." journalOrPublisher="Zoologischer Anzeiger" pageId="0" pageNumber="71495" pagination="413 - 416" refId="B7165168" refString="Verhoeff, K. W., 1908. Zwei neue Gattungen der Glomeroidea. Zoologischer Anzeiger 33: 413 - 416" title="Zwei neue Gattungen der Glomeroidea" volume="33" year="1908">Verhoeff (1908)</bibRefCitation>
from the neighbourhood of Dresden, Germany, where two females were found on limestone near a brook. In his monograph on the millipede fauna of Czechoslovakia, 
<bibRefCitation author="Lang, J." journalOrPublisher="Ceskoslovenska Akademie Ved, Praha" pageId="0" pageNumber="71495" refId="B7164795" refString="Lang, J., 1954. Mnohonozky - Diplopoda. Fauna CSR, 2. Ceskoslovenska Akademie Ved, Praha" title="Mnohonozky - Diplopoda. Fauna CSR, 2" year="1954">Lang (1954)</bibRefCitation>
presented the finding of 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. subterranea" pageId="0" pageNumber="71495" rank="species" species="subterranea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71495">G. subterranea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the only Slovak locality from the vicinity of the Bratislava City (
<normalizedToken originalValue="Malé">Male</normalizedToken>
Karpaty Mts.). However, he did not comment on the finding and attached only a picture taken from other literature (
<bibRefCitation author="Schubart, O." journalOrPublisher="Jena" pageId="0" pageNumber="71495" refId="B7165039" refString="Schubart, O., 1934. Die Tierwelt Deutschlands 28. Jena" title="Die Tierwelt Deutschlands 28." year="1934">Schubart 1934</bibRefCitation>
). Since the cited monograph contains many ambiguities and unreliable data, this information is considered doubtful (
<bibRefCitation author="Gulicka, J." journalOrPublisher="Slovak Academy of Sciences, Bratislava" pageId="0" pageNumber="71495" refId="B7164629" refString="Gulicka, J., 1986. The soil fauna of the Little Carpathians. Slovak Academy of Sciences, Bratislava" title="The soil fauna of the Little Carpathians" year="1986">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Gulička">Gulicka</normalizedToken>
1986
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Mock, A." journalOrPublisher="Myriapodologica Czecho-Slovaca" pageId="0" pageNumber="71495" pagination="25 - 38" refId="B7164865" refString="Mock, A., 2001. Millipedes of the Slovak Republic. Myriapodologica Czecho-Slovaca 1: 25 - 38" title="Millipedes of the Slovak Republic" volume="1" year="2001">Mock 2001a</bibRefCitation>
). In the area of Slovakia, it was found only recently (
<normalizedToken originalValue="Haľková">Haľkova</normalizedToken>
et al., unpublished), repeatedly, in karst springs and wetlands on karst bedrock. Detailed morphological study (including SEM), supported by molecular analysis, confirmed the identity of 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. subterranea" pageId="0" pageNumber="71495" rank="species" species="subterranea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71495">G. subterranea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, without any apparent morphological adaptations to aquatic and semi-aquatic habitat. The possibility that this species is not strictly limited to the terrestrial environment has already been suggested by 
<bibRefCitation author="Noll, W." journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen des naturwissenschaftlichen Museums der Stadt Aschaffenburg N. F." pageId="0" pageNumber="71495" pagination="3 - 26" refId="B7164955" refString="Noll, W., 1939. Die Grundwasserfauna des Maingebietes. Mitteilungen des naturwissenschaftlichen Museums der Stadt Aschaffenburg N.F. 1: 3 - 26" title="Die Grundwasserfauna des Maingebietes" volume="1" year="1939">Noll (1939)</bibRefCitation>
, although his findings were completely forgotten in recent literature. Noll mentioned the presence of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verhoeff" authorityYear="1915" class="Diplopoda" family="Glomeridae" genus="Geoglomeris" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Geoglomeris jurassica" order="Glomerida" pageId="0" pageNumber="71495" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jurassica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71495">Geoglomeris jurassica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(a younger synonym of 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. subterranea" pageId="0" pageNumber="71495" rank="species" species="subterranea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71495">G. subterranea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) in the water of three wells in Northern Bavaria, Germany. The author explained its occurrence as random, presuming the animals entered the well through crevices in the wall.
</paragraph>
